04484nam a22006015i 9780520976962DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780520976962  a(DE-B1597)577404  a(OCoLC)1248759440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML410.R23bF55 2021 7aMUS0500002bisacsh04a780.92aB2231 aFillerup, Jessie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMagician of Sound :bRavel and the Aesthetics of Illusion /cJessie Fillerup. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 20th-Century Music ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Examples, Figures, and Table -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Misdirection, or Image, Illusion, and Musical Motion -- t2 Emblems of Enchantment -- t3 The Machine Bewitched -- t4 Illusions of Form and Void -- t5 Motion, Illusion, and Phantasmagoria in La Valse -- tConclusion: Time, Space, Sortilèges -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tCALIFORNIA STUDIES IN 20TH-CENTURY MUSIC0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrench composer Maurice Ravel was described by critics as a magician, conjurer, and illusionist. Scholars have been aware of this historical curiosity, but none so far have explained why Ravel attracted such critiques or what they might tell us about how to interpret his music. Magician of Sound examines Ravel's music through the lens of illusory experience, considering how timbre, orchestral effects, figure/ground relationships, and impressions of motion and stasis might be experienced as if they were conjuring tricks. Applying concepts from music theory, psychology, philosophy, and the history of magic, Jessie Fillerup develops an approach to musical illusion that newly illuminates Ravel's fascination with machines and creates compelling links between his music and other forms of aesthetic illusion, from painting and poetry to fiction and phantasmagoria. Fillerup analyzes scenes of enchantment and illusory effects in Ravel's most popular works, including Boléro, La Valse, Daphnis et Chloé, and Rapsodie espagnole, relating his methods and musical effects to the practice of theatrical conjurers. Drawing on a rich well of primary sources, Magician of Sound provides a new interdisciplinary framework for interpreting this enigmatic composer, linking magic and music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMusic and magic. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052097696240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520976962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520976962/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075412-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZDB-23-DKUb2021